## Appendix I More Theoretical Analyses

### Expressive Power of Our Generalized Parameterization

Though the introduced coefficients \(\bm{l}_{\lambda},\bm{s}_{\lambda},\bm{b}_{\lambda}\) seem limited to guarantee the optimality of the parameterization formulation itself, we claim that the generalized parameterization \(\bm{g}_{\theta}\) in Eq. (8) can actually cover a wide range of parameterization families in the form of \(\bm{\psi}_{\theta}(\bm{x}_{\lambda},\lambda)=\bm{\alpha}(\lambda)\bm{\epsilon }_{\theta}(\bm{x}_{\lambda},\lambda)+\bm{\beta}(\lambda)\bm{x}_{\lambda}+\bm{ \gamma}(\lambda)\). Considering the paramization on \([\lambda_{s},\lambda_{t}]\), by rearranging the terms, Eq. (8) can be written as

\[\bm{g}_{\theta}(\bm{x}_{\lambda},\lambda)=e^{-\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{\lambda} \bm{s}_{\tau}\mathrm{d}\tau}\frac{\sigma_{\lambda}}{\alpha_{\lambda}}\bm{ \epsilon}_{\theta}(\bm{x}_{\lambda},\lambda)-e^{-\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{\lambda} \bm{s}_{\tau}\mathrm{d}\tau}\frac{\bm{l}_{\lambda}}{\alpha_{\lambda}}\bm{x}_{ \lambda}-\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{\lambda}e^{-\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{\lambda}\bm{s}_{ \tau}\mathrm{d}\tau}\bm{b}_{\tau}\mathrm{d}r\] (68)

We can compare the coefficients before \(\bm{\epsilon}_{\theta}\) and \(\bm{x}_{\lambda}\) in \(\bm{g}_{\theta}\) and \(\bm{\psi}_{\theta}\) to figure out how \(\bm{l}_{\lambda},\bm{s}_{\lambda},\bm{b}_{\lambda}\) corresponds to \(\bm{\alpha}(\lambda),\bm{\beta}(\lambda),\bm{\gamma}(\lambda)\). In fact, we can not directly let \(\bm{g}_{\theta}\) equal \(\bm{\psi}_{\theta}\), since when \(\lambda=\lambda_{s}\), we have \(\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{\lambda}(\cdot)=0\), and the coefficient before \(\bm{\epsilon}_{\theta}\) in \(\bm{g}_{\theta}\) is fixed. Still, \(\bm{\psi}_{\theta}\) can be equalized to \(\bm{g}_{\theta}\) by a linear transformation, which only depends on \(\lambda_{s}\) and does not affect our analyses of the discretization error and solver.

Specifically, assuming \(\bm{\psi}_{\theta}=\bm{\omega}_{\lambda_{s}}\bm{g}_{\theta}+\bm{\xi}_{ \lambda_{s}}\), by corresponding the coefficients we have

\[\begin{cases}\bm{\alpha}(\lambda)=\bm{\omega}_{\lambda_{s}}e^{-\int_{\lambda_ {s}}^{\lambda}\bm{s}_{\tau}\mathrm{d}\tau}\frac{\sigma_{\lambda}}{\alpha_{ \lambda}}\\ \bm{\beta}(\lambda)=-\bm{\omega}_{\lambda_{s}}e^{-\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{\lambda} \bm{s}_{\tau}\mathrm{d}\tau}\frac{\bm{l}_{\lambda}}{\alpha_{\lambda}}\\ \bm{\gamma}(\lambda)=-\bm{\omega}_{\lambda_{s}}\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{\lambda}e^{ -\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{\tau}\bm{s}_{\tau}\mathrm{d}\tau}\bm{b}_{\tau}\mathrm{d} r+\bm{\xi}_{\lambda_{s}}\end{cases}\Rightarrow\begin{cases}\bm{\omega}_{\lambda_{s}}=e^{ \lambda_{s}}\bm{\alpha}(\lambda_{s})\\ \bm{\xi}_{\lambda_{s}}=\bm{\gamma}(\lambda_{s})\\ \bm{l}_{\lambda}=-\sigma_{\lambda}\frac{\bm{\beta}(\lambda)}{\bm{\alpha}( \lambda)}\\ \bm{s}_{\lambda}=-1-\frac{\bm{\alpha}(\lambda)}{\bm{\alpha}(\lambda)}\\ \bm{b}_{\lambda}=-e^{-\lambda}\frac{\bm{\gamma}(\lambda)}{\bm{\alpha}(\lambda)} \end{cases}\] (69)

Therefore, as long as \(\bm{\alpha}(\lambda)\neq 0\) and \(\bm{\alpha}(\lambda),\bm{\gamma}(\lambda)\) have first-order derivatives, our proposed parameterization \(\bm{g}_{\theta}\) holds the same expressive power as \(\bm{\psi}_{\theta}\), while at the same time enabling the neat optimality criteria of \(\bm{l}_{\lambda},\bm{s}_{\lambda},\bm{b}_{\lambda}\) in Eq. (5) and Eq. (11).

### Justification of Why Minimizing First-order Discretization Error Can Help Higher-order Solver

The EMS \(\bm{s}_{\lambda}^{*}\), \(\bm{b}_{\lambda}^{*}\) in Eq. (11) are designed to minimize the first-order discretization error in Eq. (10). However, the high-order solver is actually more frequently adopted in practice (specifically, third-order in unconditional sampling, second-order in conditional sampling), since it incurs lower sampling errors by taking higher-order Taylor expansions to approximate the predictor \(\bm{g}_{\theta}\).

In the following, we show that the EMS can also help high-order solver. By Eq. (52) in Appendix B.4, the \((n+1)\)-th order local error can be expressed as

\[\hat{\bm{x}}_{t}-\bm{x}_{t} =\alpha_{t}\bm{A}(\lambda_{s},\lambda_{t})\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{ \lambda_{t}}\bm{E}_{\lambda_{s}}(\lambda)\left(\bm{g}_{\theta}(\bm{x}_{\lambda _{s}},\lambda)-\bm{g}_{\theta}(\bm{x}_{\lambda_{s}},\lambda_{s})\right)\mathrm{d}\lambda\] (70) \[-\alpha_{t}\bm{A}(\lambda_{s},\lambda_{t})\sum_{k=1}^{n}\left( \sum_{l=1}^{n}(\bm{R}_{n}^{-1})_{kl}(\bm{g}_{\theta}(\bm{x}_{\lambda_{i_{l}}}, \lambda_{i_{l}})-\bm{g}_{\theta}(\bm{x}_{\lambda_{s}},\lambda_{s}))\right) \int_{\lambda_{s}}^{\lambda_{t}}\bm{E}_{\lambda_{s}}(\lambda)\frac{(\lambda- \lambda_{s})^{k}}{k!}\mathrm{d}\lambda\]

By Newton-Leibniz theorem, it is equivalent to

\[\hat{\bm{x}}_{t}-\bm{x}_{t} =\alpha_{t}\bm{A}(\lambda_{s},\lambda_{t})\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{ \lambda_{t}}\bm{E}_{\lambda_{s}}(\lambda)\left(\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{\lambda}g_ {\theta}^{(1)}(x_{\tau},\tau)\mathrm{d}\tau\right)\mathrm{d}\lambda\] (71) \[-\alpha_{t}\bm{A}(\lambda_{s},\lambda_{t})\sum_{k=1}^{n}\left( \sum_{l=1}^{n}(\bm{R}_{n}^{-1})_{kl}\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{\lambda_{i_{l}}}g_{ \theta}^{(1)}(x_{\lambda},\lambda)\mathrm{d}\lambda\right)\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{ \lambda_{t}}\bm{E}_{\lambda_{s}}(\lambda)\frac{(\lambda-\lambda_{s})^{k}}{k!} \mathrm{d}\lambda\]

We assume that the estimated EMS are bounded (in the order of \(\mathcal{O}(1)\), Assumption B.2 in Appendix B.1), which is empirically confirmed as in Section 4.2. By the definition of \(\bm{g}_{\theta}\) in Eq. (8), we have \(\bm{g}_{\theta}^{(1)}(\bm{x}_{\tau},\tau)=e^{-\int_{\lambda_{s}}^{\tau}\bm{s} _{\tau}\mathrm{d}\tau}\left(\bm{f}_{\theta}^{(1)}(\bm{x}_{\tau},\tau)-\bm{s}_ {\tau}\bm{f}_{\theta}(\bm{x}_{\tau},\tau)-\bm{b}_{\tau}\right)\). Therefore, Eq. (11) controls \(\|\bm{g}_{\theta}^{(1)}\|_{2}\) and further controls \(\|\hat{\bm{x}}_{t}-\bm{x}_{t}\|_{2}\), since other terms are only dependent on the EMS and are bounded.

